aport, and Mary Douglas to literary critics Frederick Turner, Leo Marx, and R.W.B. Lewis, Jordan explores the promise of restoration, both as a way of reversing environmental damage and as a context for negotiating our relationship with nature. Exploring restoration not only as a technology but also as an experience and a performing art, Jordan claims that it is the indispensable key to conservation. At the same time, he argues, restoration is valuable because it provides a context for confronting the most troubling aspects of our relationship with nature. For this reason, it offers a way past the essentially sentimental idea of nature that environmental thinkers have taken for granted since the time of Emerson and Muir.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aRestoration ecology. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh  aanimal population.  abiological diversity.  acommunion with nature.  acommunity.  aconservation.  aecology.  aecosystem.  aenvironment.  aenvironmentalism.  aflora and fauna.  ahabitat.  ahumans in nature.  aindigenous culture.  aindigenous people.  ainvasive species.  alandscape.  ameditation.  anatural world.  anature.  anonfiction.  aplains.  aplants.  aprairies.  areinhabitation.  areintroduction.  arelationship with nature.  arelaxation.  arestoration ecology.  arestoration.  ascience.  aspirituality.  atidal marsh.  avegetation.  awetlands.  awild animals.  awilderness.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023320140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092848040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520928480423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520928480/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  Univer